<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="About_Censorship">About Censorship</span></h2>
<ul><li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/6678" class="extiw" title="ebook:6678">Nonsenseorship</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a>  (Various authors)</li>
<li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/8495" class="extiw" title="ebook:8495">Books Fatal to Their Authors</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> P. H.Ditchfield</li>
<li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/2901" class="extiw" title="ebook:2901">Studies and Essays: Censorship and Art</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> John Galsworthy</li>
<li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/608" class="extiw" title="ebook:608">Areopagitica<br />
A speech for the Liberty of Unlicensed Printing to the Parliament of England</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> by John Milton</li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Banned_or_Persecuted_Books">Banned or Persecuted Books</span></h2>
<ul><li> Thomas Paine
<ul><li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/3742" class="extiw" title="ebook:3742">The Rights of Man</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> This book was responsible for Paine being indicted for treason in England in 1792.</li>
<li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/3743" class="extiw" title="ebook:3743">The Age of Reason</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> A number of publishers were prosecuted in England for publishing this argument for atheism.</li></ul></li></ul>
<ul><li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/authors/London_Jack" class="extiw" title="author:London Jack">Jack London</a>'s writings frequently had socialist themes, and were the subject of bans by European dictatorships in the 1920s and 1930s: Yugoslavia banned all his works.
<ul><li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/215" class="extiw" title="ebook:215">The Call of the Wild</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> - cheap editions banned by the Italian government in 1929</li>
<li> <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1164" class="extiw" title="ebook:1164">The Iron Heel</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> - burned by the Nazis</li></ul></li></ul>
